JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 101
IS  - 4
SP  - 835
EP  - 860
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The paper shows how career concerns rather than effort aversion can induce a natural incongruity in risk preferences between managers and superiors. A model, based on learning about managerial talent, is developed to study second-best contractual remedies. We show that the optimal wage contract is an option of the value of the manager's human capital for insurance reasons and that consequently rationing of capital is often required to counterbalance the manager's resulting incentive to overinvest. Rationing is strictly superior to price decentralization, offering one reason for the prevalence of centralized capital budgeting procedures.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1884180
ER  - 



